{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5be5fbf8-e40d-45ba-8bc6-1c19d786823b","content":"The root cause is clear from the report. Every `dotnet build` CLI invocation starts a **new MSBuild process** and re-evaluates the project graph from scratch. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild host.\n\nThe key difference: `dotnet build` defaults to `/nodeReuse:false`, discarding MSBuild worker nodes after each build. VS reuses them.\n\nHere are the fixes, in order of impact:\n\n### 1. Enable MSBuild node reuse (biggest win)\n\nCreate a `Directory.Build.rsp` file so all CLI builds automatically reuse MSBuild nodes:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01WJXTe8mZiwTwzjz67mCPWw","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Fixing CLI build performance"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01E6gJmAHKHW9JWvtv2yn4Ex","name":"create","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-9677a07198e34a92b89f4e37b0957ead/Directory.Build.rsp","file_text":"-nodeReuse:true\n"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"create a new file at /tmp/sv-9677a07198e34a92b89f4e37b0957ead/Directory.Build.rsp."}],"interactionId":"b4e5d594-8f12-479c-bd71-cae44efce9f8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer is reporting that `dotnet build` CLI builds are slow for incremental builds, even when nothing has changed. Visual Studio builds the same project almost instantly.\n\nThe key issue here is well-known in the .NET ecosystem: every `dotnet build` invocation starts a new MSBuild process, re-evaluates the project graph, and does SDK resolution. Visual Studio keeps a persistent MSBuild server process (design-time build host) that caches the project graph.\n\nThe solution is to use the **MSBuild Server** (also known as the MSBuild Build Server or `dotnet build-server`). Starting with .NET 8+ / MSBuild 17.8+, there's a feature flag to keep an MSBuild server process running between builds:\n\n\nSetting the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` environment variable enables the MSBuild server, which keeps the MSBuild process warm between builds and avoids the overhead of re-evaluation and process startup. For the development workflow, using `dotnet watch` is also effective since it keeps MSBuild warm and only rebuilds what's changed. Build server with `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` to keep the MSBuild process alive between invocations. The real issue is that the CLI starts fresh each time while VS maintains a long-lived process, so the most practical fix for the dev loop is using `dotnet watch` to avoid repeated startup overhead, or enabling node reuse through `MSBuildReuseNode=true` since it's disabled by default in CLI builds but enabled in Visual Studio. Disabling node reuse is the main culprit slowing down CLI builds since each invocation spins up fresh MSBuild nodes, so I should recommend enabling it via a `Directory.Build.rsp` file that applies to all builds, while also suggesting `dotnet watch` for faster iteration during development.","outputTokens":1336,"requestId":"280C:12EB87:5C3D33B:63B4741:69FBE27A"},"id":"e95e6166-ed82-44b9-833b-842385a9b4d3","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:53:40.927Z","parentId":"a4813283-2739-4c85-9be4-35b7eb3ca7d5"}
